\multicolumn{6}{c}{}\\\hline
&Mon&Tues&Wed&Thurs&Fri\\\hline

Carl&X&X&&X&X\\\hline
\end{tabular}
inference:
To find the day on which the most people can attend a meeting, we need to count the number of 'X' marks for each day.
Monday: Anna has an X, Carl has an X. Bill has no X. So 2 people have X's.
Tuesday: Anna has no X, Bill has an X, Carl has an X. So 2 people have X's.
Wednesday: Anna has no X, Bill has no X, Carl has no X. So 0 people have X's.
Thursday: Anna has no X, Bill has an X, Carl has an X. So 2 people have X's.
Friday: Anna has no X, Bill has an X, Carl has an X. So 2 people have X's.

Wednesday has 0 people with X's, so the most people can attend on Wednesday.

Final Answer: $\boxed{Wednesday}$
ground_truth: On each day but Wednesday, only one person can attend a meeting. On Wednesday, two people can. Thus, the day on which the most people can attend a meeting is $\boxed{\text{Wednesday}}.$
